\begin{abstract}
We argue based on theoretical considerations and analysis of
experimental data that quasiparticle excitations near the nodes
determine the low temperature properties in the superconducting
state of cuprates. Quantum effects of phase fluctuations are shown
to be quantitatively important, but thermal effects are small for
$T \ll T_c$. An anisotropic
superfluid Fermi liquid phenomenology is presented for 
the effect of quasiparticle interactions on the temperature and doping
dependence of the low $T$ penetration depth.
